      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>$\\mathrm{CH}_4$</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>$\\mathrm{XeF}_2$ has $s p^3 d$ hybridisation involving 5 orbitals (one of them $d$ ). The rest are $s p^3$ (no $d$-orbitals).</p>\n<p><img alt=\"BITSAT 2025 Chemistry - Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure Question 1 English Explanation\" src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mnqh7vcu/e1b972f3-4b0f-4a71-9de5-4cb91c91db22/1847a9e0-3386-11f1-9cee-13299b95b990/file-jaoe38c1mnqh7vcv.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mnqh7vcu/e1b972f3-4b0f-4a71-9de5-4cb91c91db22/1847a9e0-3386-11f1-9cee-13299b95b990/file-jaoe38c1mnqh7vcv.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\"></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2025,
    "yearKey": "bitsat-2025",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "The bond dissociation energy of $ X_{2}, Y_{2} $ and $ X Y $ are in the ratio of $ 1: 0.5: 1 . \\Delta H $ for the formation of $ X Y $ is $ -200 \\mathrm{~kJ} / \\mathrm{mol} $. The bond dissociation energy of $ X_{2} $ will be",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$ 200 \\mathrm{~kJ} / \\mathrm{mol} $"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$ 100 \\mathrm{~kJ} / \\mathrm{mol} $"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$ 400 \\mathrm{~kJ} / \\mathrm{mol} $"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$ 800 \\mathrm{~kJ} / \\mathrm{mol} $"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>To find the bond dissociation energy of $ X_2 $, let's assume the bond dissociation energy of $ X_2 $ is $ a \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $.</p>\n\n<p><p>Therefore, $ \\text{BE}(X_2) = a \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $.</p></p>\n<p><p>Given that the bond dissociation energy ratios are $ 1:0.5:1 $, then:</p></p>\n<p><p>$ \\text{BE}(Y_2) = 0.5a \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $</p></p>\n<p><p>$ \\text{BE}(XY) = a \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $.</p></p>\n\n<p>We know that the formation reaction of $ XY $ is:</p>\n<p>$ \\frac{1}{2} X_2 + \\frac{1}{2} Y_2 \\rightarrow XY, \\quad \\Delta H = -200 \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $</p>\n<p>Using the enthalpy change equation:</p>\n<p>$ \\Delta_r H = \\text{BE}(\\text{Reactants}) - \\text{BE}(\\text{Products}) $</p>\n<p>Substituting the bond dissociation energies into the equation gives:</p>\n<p>$ \\Delta_r H = \\frac{1}{2} \\text{BE}(X_2) + \\frac{1}{2} \\text{BE}(Y_2) - \\text{BE}(XY) $</p>\n<p>Plugging in the known values:</p>\n<p>$ -200 = \\frac{a}{2} + \\frac{0.5a}{2} - a $</p>\n<p>Simplifying:</p>\n<p>$ -200 = \\frac{a}{2} + \\frac{0.25a}{2} - a = \\frac{a}{2} + \\frac{a}{4} - a $</p>\n<p>Combine the terms:</p>\n<p>$ -200 = \\frac{a}{2} + \\frac{0.25a}{2} - \\frac{2a}{2} $</p>\n<p>$ -200 = \\frac{0.5a + 0.25a - 2a}{2} = \\frac{-0.75a}{2} $</p>\n<p>Solving for $ a $:</p>\n<p>$ -200 = \\frac{-0.75a}{2} $</p>\n<p>$ -200 \\times 2 = -0.75a $</p>\n<p>$ -400 = -0.75a $</p>\n<p>Dividing both sides by $-0.75$:</p>\n<p>$ a = \\frac{400}{0.75} = 800 \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $</p>\n<p>Thus, the bond dissociation energy of $ X_2 $ is $ 800 \\, \\text{kJ/mol} $.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2024,
    "yearKey": "bitsat-2024",
    "difficulty": null
  },
